    <h2 class="film-theme">Human Interest
</h2>
		<p class="film-content">
		When Tatum first learns of the Minosa situation, he gives insightful commentary into human nature to his protoge Herbie; “You pick up the paper, you read about 84 men or 284, or a million men, like in a Chinese famine. You read it, but it doesn't stay with you. One man's different, you want to know all about him. That's human interest”. Had Leo Minosa been trapped with a group of cave divers, his story would have been less appealing as the audience would not have personally connected with Leo. With a large group, the numbers become overwhelming. But with a single individual facing terrible odds, Tatum is able to weaponize that emotional connection to fabricate a story that captivated the nation. Additionally, the onlookers that come to the site of the situation to spectate seem to only care about their own entertainment and their stake in the situation rather than for Leo himself. Al Ferderber and his family are the first tourists to come to the cave to watch the rescue operation, and when interviewed by the radio station, it becomes clear that Al only cares for his reputation as “the first” to witness the operation rather than for a successful outcome. The other spectators even bring in a literal circus and music entertainment as they await Leo’s rescue, seemingly caring more for their own amusement than making sure that Leo makes it home safely. It is only when Tatum realizes the extent of the rampant consumerism and sensationalism does he put a stop to the circus of his own making; “Leo Minosa is dead. He died a quarter of an hour ago with the drill just ten feet away. There is nothing we can do anymore. There is nothing anybody can do anymore. Now go home, all of you. The circus is over!”
</p>

